 4\n84 24 Chain Store Dav.\u25ba 44 44 44 t 4\n25 174 Ch Nat Asaonv... 24,4 234 244+ 4\n25 174 Chat Ph All nv.... 194 19 19-4\n444 244 Cities Ser .30a 284 274 284\n21 84 Col Oil A Gaa vtc.. 84 84 84\n544 334 Col Picturee vtc... 384 384 384\u2014 4\n64 34 Coml AS war...... 34 34 34\n64 24 Cons Instrum....* 24 24 24\u2014 4\n174 6 Cord Corp 84 8 8 -4\n744 32 Cosden Oil 444 44 444- 4\n74 54 Creole Petrol....- <4 64 64- 4\n344 15 Crocker Wheeler.. 174 174 174\u2014 4\n1 4 Crown Cent Pet... 4 4 4\n514 34 Cuneo Press 404 404 404- 4\nGROUP HANDLES\nISSUE\nA banking group comprising\nDillon, Read Co., the National\nCity Company, Lane, Piper and\nJaffray, Inc., First Securities Cor\nporation of St. Paul, and Minne\napolis and Banc Northwest Com\npany is offering today 14,106,000\nMinneapolis, St. Paul and Sault\nSte. Marie Railway Company first\nrefunding mortgage s'/ 2 per cent\nbonds, series \u201cB\u201d, at a price of\n99 and interest.\nThe bonds are due July 1. 1978,\nand are non-callable prior to July\n1, 1958. Payment of interest is\nguaranteed by the Canadian Pa\ncific Railway Company.\nThe present offering will in\ncrease the amount of series \u201cB\u201d\nbonds outstanding to 812,106,000.\nApplication will be made to list\nthe issue on the New York Stock\nExchange.\nTwo Patent Suits\nAgainst R. K. O,\nWILMINGTON, Del., July 31.\nGeneral Talking Pictures, Inc.,\nand the De Forest Phonofilms,\nInc., filed suits in the United\nStates district court here today\nseeking an accounting, restoration\nof property and a permanent in\njunction charging infringements\nof 18 patents. The R. C. A.\nPhotophone, Inc., and the RrKO\nRadio Pictures, Inc., were named\ndefendants.\nThe R. C. A. Photophone firm\nwas charged with infringements\nof six patents, most of them for\nrecording and reproducing ap\nparatus invented by De Forest\nand Dr. Reis, and in the showing\nof talkie films. The R-KO firm\nwas charged with the infringe\nment of 10 patents,, also used in\nmodern motion pictures. The\nsuits are the outgrowth of a re\ncent decision made here by Judge\nHugh M. Morris favorable to the\ncomplainant firms.\nTexas Gas Utilities\nSends Gas to Mexico\nThe work of laying the new\nChittim Field-Eagle pass natural\ngas pipeline of Texds Gas Utili\nties Co., subsidiary of Appala\nchian Gas Corp., was commenced\nyesterday.\nThe line will run through the\nnew $6,000,000 Naverick county\nirrigation project en route to\nEagle Pass, continuing on to the\nmiddle of the International\nBridge, where present plans call\nfor the delivery of natural gas\nin the city of Piedras Negras\nthrough a Mexican distributing\nor else continuation of\nthe line by the company into\nMexican territory.\nNAMED FISCAL AGENT\nThe Chatham-Phenix National\nBank and Trust Company has\nbeen appointed fiscal ngent for\na tame of 616461.502.67 Munici\nty of Buenm Aires six months\n1 mt cw. ttuawiry goM notes.\nJanuary 1 MM\nBusiness Outlook\nI t \u2014J\nCurrent indications of the\ntrend in various divisions of in\ndustry and trade are summarized\nby the Standard Statistics Com\npany, of New York, from its first\nof August resume of the outlook\nfor important lines, as follows:\nAgricultural Implements\u2014lt is\nnot expected that this year\u2019s last\nhalf profits will equal those of a\nyear ago.\nAircraft\u2014The preponderance of\nmanufacturing companies are\noperating at a loss and the pros\npects hold scant promise of any\nmaterial improvement developing\ntor months to come, at least.\nEngine manufacturers are much\nmore favorably situated than are\n1 the craft builders.\nApparel\u2014Profit margins of ap\nparel companies will continue\nnarrow, pending downward re\nadjustment in their costs.\nAutomobiles \u2014Only moderate\nrelative improvement is looked\nfor in the final three months of\nthe year.\nAutomobile Parts\u2014A number\nof producers will have difficulty\nin reporting anything earned\nduring the current three months\u2019\nperiod.\nAutomobile Tires\u2014Total tire\nsales in 1930 probably will be in\nthe neighborhood of 60,000,000,\nrepresenting a sharp reduction\nfrom approximately 71,000.000 in\n1929.\nBuilding\u2014Evidence is still lack\ning to indicate a Sustained up\ntrend of building and, excepting\ncement, the major building ma\nterials are weakly situated.\nChemicals\u2014Few producers will\nreport larger earnings during the\nbalance of the current year than\nin the corresponding 1929 period.\nThe longer term sales and earn\nings outlook, however, continues\nattractive.\nCoal\u2014 Earnings of bituminous\nproducers during the next few\nmonths will leave much to be de\nsired.\nCopper-d-Full year 1930 earn\nings will probably be far below\nthose of the preceding year.\nCotton\u2014On the whole there\nseems little prospect for rising\ncotton prices (barring crop dis\naster).\nElectric Equipment\u2014Taken as\na whole resillts during the bal\nance of 1930 are likely to com\npare unfavorably with those of\n1929.\nFarm Products (grain)\u2014There\nseems no basis for any sustained\nrecovery in wheat values, because\nof the weakened statistical posi\ntion. No sharp rally in corn\nprices is in early prospect, even\nthough present quotations should\nbe maintained.\nFertilizers\u2014The outlook for the\ncurrent fiscal period is made ex\ntremely uncertain by the ex\npected reduction in this year\u2019s\nfarm income.\nLead and Zinc\u2014There seems no\nincentive to make other than\nnear term purchases at the pres\nent time.\nLeather\u2014Successful passage of\nthe tariff act is a constructive\ndevelopment in the longer tehn\nnuHnok for the tanners.\nMacfencry\u2014An imprwed\nttamat to as\u00dfarat tn th* trade.\nTHK WASHINGTON TIMES\n-ta u. \u00bb.u s?\u00ab-\nO\u2014\u2014\n1624 SIH D**r* ACo new... 794 78 78 -2\n84 24 D*Fortet Rad,.., 34 34 34\n94 44 D*t Aircraft.l.... 54 5 54\n234 124 Dowries Aircr M.. 204 204 204+ 4\nl(X) 70 *DOw Chara 2 10 70 70\u20143\n444 314 DresserMf*B.... 35 344 35\n134 4\u2019 Du bill er Co nd..... 4