014The industry\nshould be one of the first to\nbenefit from any general trade re\ncovery..\nPaper\u2014On the whole the in\ndustry gives evidence of having\ndefinitely turned the comer, after\nsome two years of adversity.\nPetroleum\u2014Considerably more\nencouraging are the recent trends\ndominant in the oil industry.\nRadio-r-Prospects foY the second\nhalf year point to moderately\nfavorable results for the strongly\nsituated concerns. Tube manufac\nturers, however, do not appear to\nbe in so strong a position.\nRailroads\u2014With\u2019 any expansion\nin fourth-quarter traffic, earnings\ntoward the end of the year could\neasily record gains in comparison\nwith the downward trend in ef\nfect during the closing months of\n1929.\nRailroad Equipment\u2014Lower net\nincome for the full year is in\npospect.\nRayon Earnings of rayon\nproducers for the final half of\n1930 will fall considerably under\nthose of the corresponding 1929\nperiod.\nRetail Trade \u2014Aggregate profits\nof retailers for the latter half,\nor for the full year, will hardly\nmake favorable comparisons with\n1929 income.\nRubber\u2014There is no convinc\ning evidence available to indicate\na sustained near term advance.\nShipping\u2014Entirely satisfactory\nincome is assured for those yards\nwhich are in a position to benefit\nfrom the expansion of our deep\nwater fleet during the next two\nor three years.'\nSilk\u2014Prices between now and\nthe end of 1930 should stabilize\nat current or slightly higher\nlevels.\nSteel\u2014Earnings for the current\nhalf year will probably be even\nless favorable than at present.\nSugar\u2014Slow demand and re\nduced values will cause refiners\nto report reduced profits' during\nthe balance of the current year.\nTheaters\u2014Net income of pro\nducers this year will attain levels\nsubstantially in excess of the 1929\namount.\nTin\u2014Quotations continue to ex\nhibit more weakness than strength\nand little improvement is expected\nunless immediate curtailment of\noutout materializes.\nTobacco\u2014Aggregate sales ad\nvance in the cigarette industry\nduring the final half of 1930\nshould materially exceed that of\nthe June half.\nUtilities\u2014For the full -year no\nmore than slight decreases from\n1929 earnings of electric light and\npower companies can be expected.\nThe extent of improvement in gas\ndistribution in the fall depends to\na large extent on the recovery of\ntrade activity. The telephone in\ndustry has been making food prog\nress and th* Is\u20143ms outlook is\nfororabta.\n\u2019\u2019wrii 3 Low\" DtvMMd State L*w till C***v\n34 1 Mavte\u00dfotl \u2018l4 14 14\n694 48 MayttowarA*2s... CO 60 60 \u2014l4\n744 554 M4ad Johnion 3a.. <24 724 724+ H\n224 104 M\u00abj\u00bb\u00bbhteNG..,.. 13 13* 13-4\n24 JH WhteW Trod 'l4 14 14+ 4\n334 254 Mtetg l \u00abo*-.- M~ 4\n164 84 llotaloWlMlJV 13 13 II\n114 44 MHBt*P*tAv... 6 6 6-4\n38 25M Mid WUtrf\u00df*b... 294 294 294- 4\n154 Mid St Pr a\u00abw 2... 194 194 194+ 4\n334 254 Milter A Son* 2.... -7 27 27 4\n364 15 Mo KPL 16\u00bb1.. 214 214 214+ 4\n4 4 Mountain AG.... 4 4 4-4\nN\n124 64 NatAm*r2. t 4 64 64- 4\n214 84 Nat Aviation 94 84 84- 14\n'2O 12 Nat Family S I.W. 12 12 U\n414 254 Nat Fu*l Gax 1.... 31 CO4 'B4- 4\n1034 1004 NatPALtof \u00ab\u00bb4 Wl4 1014+ 4\n15 12 Nat Short T 144 14 144- 4\n35 29 Nat Sus Rf 2..... 30 30 1,6-14\n224 154 Nat Transit 1.... 1\u00ab4 164 164- 4\n914 654 N J Zin* n 67 67. 67 -4\n74 34 NMttSArtt..... 34 34 34\n1414 79 N\u00abwmont Mia 4a. 874 874 874- 4\n42 204 Niwnort 3 224 224 224- 4\n164 104 N T P*trol 1 114 114 114+ 4\n18 7 NYRABLInoJ.. 94 \u00bb4 \u00bb4- 4\n244 154 Nia A Hud Pw .40. 164 164 164- 4\n64 4 Nia Hud PA war.. 44 44 44\u2014 4\n214 12 Nia Sh of Md T 40.. 134 13 11 4\n444 204 Noranda Mino* 3.. 24 i 34 234- 4\nJ 2 NA Avia A war... 3 3 3\nH 3 No Am Cemt..... 44 4 44\n44 \u201d24 North Europo Oil. 24 24 24- 4\n344 224 Novadol A*\u00abn* 2.. 30H 304 304\nO\n14 4 OhioCoDDer...... 4 4 4\n344 324 Ohio Oil a. \u00a324 324 324\n184 7